	<div id="comment_top_64734986" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64734986" name="comment_link_64734986" href="//linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23433068&amp;cid=64734986" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64734986)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64734986" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64734986); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~DamnOregonian">DamnOregonian</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~DamnOregonian">( 963763 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64734986"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64734986">Massive. One of my ongoing projects is a software DPDK data and control plane.<br>
I can get ~10gbps out of a mid-level Xeon core.<br>
<br>
Of course, the trick with DPDK isn't that it was moved out of the kernel.<br>
It's that it's using polling-mode drivers.<br>
A CPU sits in a literal busy loop just looking at the NIC ring buffer. Interrupts are disabled.<br>
<br>
So that's the cost to doing that- as many cores as you have servicing the ring buffers are sitting there pegged at 100% utilization.<br>
Doesn't really matter if it's in the</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64734986">

</div>
</div>

